Title:
Defender’s different Detection Mechanisms

Type:
Blog Post

Short Summary (4–8 sentences max):
- This post analyzes Microsoft Defender for Endpoint (MDE) behavior by interpreting ETW logs collected with the author’s EDRi (EDR-Introspection) framework, which monitors MsMpEng.exe activity.  
- It compares four test attacks (Cobalt Strike loader and LSASS dumper, each with/without bypass techniques) to identify which are detected and what Defender does in response (e.g., on-disk detection vs. runtime freezing after LSASS access/MiniDumpWriteDump).  
- The core contribution is a mapping of recurring Microsoft-Antimalware-Engine ETW events (stream scan, emulation, MetaStore operations, cloud/SpyNet reporting) into a consistent sequence that approximates Defender’s decision pipeline.  
- It highlights that emulation-related memory allocation/protection changes occur inside MsMpEng and that MsMpEng’s process memory reads are preceded by NtOpenProcess calls observable in Kernel-Audit ETW, with “desiredaccess” providing strong hints about the next action.  
- The author proposes that defenders/attackers could predict MDE actions using only Kernel-Audit-API-Calls ETW, enabling “AURA/BITE” malware concepts (inferring EDR intent from access patterns).  
- Useful for red teamers and security researchers studying Defender internals/telemetry, and for blue teamers validating what ETW signals reveal about EDR behavior.

Technical Focus:
- ETW telemetry analysis (Microsoft-Antimalware-Engine, Kernel-Audit-API-Calls)
- MsMpEng.exe introspection and ntdll hooking (EDRi framework)
- Defender emulation/heuristics pipeline (stream scan, UfsScanFile/UfsScanProc, MOAC)
- MetaStore identifier storage/query and hash extraction (GetHashes)
- SpyNet/Microsoft cloud verdict reporting
- Process access rights (“desiredaccess”) correlation to subsequent NtQueryInformationProcess behavior

Use Cases:
- Reverse-engineer and model Defender/MDE detection workflow from ETW traces
- Identify which stage triggers detection (disk/static vs. emulation vs. behavior/memory)
- Build detections around suspicious MsMpEng access patterns (process opens, memory reads)
- Evaluate bypass techniques (obfuscation, “deconditioning”) against Defender responses
- Research “EDR intent inference” via access-rights telemetry (AURA/BITE hypothesis)

Keywords:
Microsoft Defender for Endpoint, MDE, MsMpEng.exe, ETW, Microsoft-Antimalware-Engine, Microsoft-Windows-Kernel-Audit-API-Calls, PsOpenProcess, desiredaccess, NtOpenProcess, NtQueryInformationProcess, UfsScanFile, UfsScanProc, MOAC, MetaStore, SpyNet, GetHashes, emulation, heuristics, MiniDumpWriteDump, LSASS dumping, Cobalt Strike loader, ntdll hooking, EDRi, EDR-Introspection, AURA malware, BITE malware